Conclusion of the Summit of Unasur no publication of the Declaration of Lima
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and theoretically from the seven present ruling should be signed.
Eastwood repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the VI ordinary session of Heads of State and Government leaders of Unasur. Sources at the heads of State and President Office shared initially with, that they would pass it after the exam, then however said that it would be released at a certain time on the Web site of the Peruvian Government.
Questions about the text, they stated that the content, was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala in short statements to the press.
The access of journalists to provide information about the Summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the image of the President meeting without sound with the message "private session, limited audio" was transferred to the press room.
The little information that circulated among the journalists, were obtained by the press officers of some of the of the Unasur Governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press officer.
The only document that was circulated during the day, was the list of the participating Presidents, causing discomfort for hundreds of various national and international media journalists demanded more information.
Then, the President of Peru sent an email with the "final Declaration" of the Summit, which however was the statement by Humala and not the official document at the end of the Summit the media.
Last October, Peru was host of III Summit South America - Arab countries (ASPA), and also on this occasion, nor was released despite the strong request by the press of the so-called Declaration of Lima, which it had announced previously.
