On two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems for the journalists were present, they limited the access to information but to a high degree.
The Summit ended with the common commitment of Chile and Peru, to accept a judgment of the Court of Justice of the Hague, which attaches a border conflict between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the ICJ's decision, which begins on Monday in the Hague, in the process, ushered in Lima to Santiago, to listen to the arguments of both sides.
"We will follow the verdict on the differences which we currently make this International Court of Justice, and perform," Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will remain a country that adheres to the international rule of law, seeking peaceful solutions to disputes, agreements and submits to the international courts", adds Piñera and greeted Humala with a handshake before the flags of both countries.
Both President, confirmed that it would abide the ICJ, came after Colombia had filed a lawsuit against the agreement of Bogotá after a decision over the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it a serious mistake, wherein it agreed to comply with the judgments of the International Court.
The Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner were present at the Summit.
Paraguay, which is excluded in 2011 after the deposition of President Fernando Lugo of the Unasur, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the Summit shortly after midday in Lima.
The head of State, made the final document wherein it announced that 16 decisions is taken and the action lines for 31 projects between the South American countries over a set amount of investment by a total of $17 billion.
To the taken decisions, he said that the countries of the Unasur "will undertake important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He announced that measures would be promoted, "cooperation in the fight against insecurity in the cities, and against the organized to improve cross-border crimes, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and in the case of natural disasters together and efficiently to act".
With the crisis in Europe "economic consolidation (in Latin America) accept no triumphant trains, but should serve to expand our production capacity and to show our peoples a better future", Humala added.
"We have decided, sollen...und therefore unite our countries a series of 31 emblematic projects to give priority, which improve the spatial connections in South America, especially in rural and frontier areas and new economies develop," said the Peruvian President, in a statement read out.
These projects include five Peruvian, who would be on the cross of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and of which two for a better connection with Ecuador to provide, although he gave no further details.
As well, the final document made reference to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country is used for its recovery in the Union of South American Nations", which it is currently excluded.
The necessity that Latin America continues to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations, was another aspect that was emphasized at the Summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said prior to his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting on Saturday in Mexico with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict following a judgement of the ICJ of Bogotá in question, respectfully.
"Maybe I will hit me tomorrow (Saturday) with the President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We will review all of these ways – they are not exclusive, and talks with Nicaragua necessitate also the agreement with Nicaragua," he pointed out.
"I hope the President Ortega to be able to say that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they have the intention to be present at the taking of Office of the new President of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
